1
00:00:01,010 --> 00:00:17,754
Foundation Course 2, Talk 6, Buddhism, Belief or Faith I wonder what you think would happen in the world if all the religious systems, ideologies, philosophies, psychologies, you name it, all the ismologies, were to disappear.

2
00:00:18,414 --> 00:00:19,957
Do you think we'd be any the poorer for it?

3
00:00:20,878 --> 00:00:23,140
Or do you think we would somehow start afresh?

4
00:00:24,001 --> 00:00:25,544
Or would we return to a barbarism?

5
00:00:26,545 --> 00:00:30,931
I suppose the underlying question is, how did we get where we are in the first place?

6
00:00:31,452 --> 00:00:40,718
According to some religious systems, truths are revealed to us by supernatural means, but the Buddha said that all his discoveries were realized through his own endeavor and his alone.

7
00:00:41,420 --> 00:00:46,473
That's why we call him the Sammasambuddho, the fully self-enlightened one.

8
00:00:46,454 --> 00:00:53,853
Furthermore, he was quite clear that whatever he discovered concerning the fact and the end of suffering could also be discovered by each individual.

9
00:00:54,435 --> 00:01:02,758
The truth, the Dhamma, is said to be to be realized by the wise for themselves.

10
00:01:04,206 --> 00:01:06,510
This is a very important point in Buddhist understanding.

11
00:01:06,890 --> 00:01:09,253
No matter what the Buddha taught, he was not a saviour.

12
00:01:09,873 --> 00:01:12,296
He could not end our personal suffering for us.

13
00:01:12,656 --> 00:01:17,161
Each person has to find that end for themselves by their own endeavour.

14
00:01:17,561 --> 00:01:19,343
The Buddhas only point the way.

15
00:01:23,408 --> 00:01:27,091
The way, the truth, the Dhamma can be a very subjective thing.

16
00:01:27,680 --> 00:01:36,594
If we begin to study the ismologies, all these isms and ologies that have been developed, to the impartial mind it's no easy task to discover the truth as an objective thing.

17
00:01:37,576 --> 00:01:44,388
Unfortunately, human beings can't point to something and say, that's it, that's the truth, the ultimate transcendent truth.

18
00:01:45,170 --> 00:01:49,737
If it were so, we'd have no disagreement such as whether there is a personal God or not.

19
00:01:50,512 --> 00:02:06,114
To make it easier for us within the scope of this talk, in which we're trying to decide whether Buddhism is a belief system or a theory meditators are trying to prove true for themselves, I'd like to use the Buddha's own description taken from a discourse I shall be quoting more fully later on.

20
00:02:06,134 --> 00:02:14,004
Truth is that which, after observation and analysis, agrees with reason and is conducive to the good and benefit of all.

21
00:02:14,844 --> 00:02:24,240
This is the Dharma, the truth, the law, and its noble characteristics are that it makes sense, it's reasonable, and that it is to the benefit of all.

22
00:02:25,481 --> 00:02:35,638
I'm sure that most philosophers and religious leaders would agree to this baseline definition, but the Buddha, of course, means that it should be the aim of all individuals to come to such realization for themselves.

23
00:02:36,530 --> 00:02:50,368
What has been essential then in the past to the development of all the systems, and essential to any future development, even if there is almost complete wipe-out of knowledge, not so unthinkable in our nuclear age, is the human desire to realize the truth.

24
00:02:51,350 --> 00:03:01,844
If a person living now does not have that desire in them, then all the religions, philosophies and so on are indeed of no avail anyway, since without that desire a person simply won't seek.

25
00:03:03,664 --> 00:03:06,647
Marx said that religion was an opium of the people.

26
00:03:07,549 --> 00:03:11,973
It put them into a pleasant dream state, a delusion in which they could be easily manipulated.

27
00:03:11,993 --> 00:03:17,179
A lot of people would argue that that's what seems to have happened to Marxism and other communist ideologies themselves.

28
00:03:17,960 --> 00:03:24,866
The underlying question here seems to be, why do people become followers and never leaders, disciples and never masters?

29
00:03:26,368 --> 00:03:30,312
I'm not here suggesting some anarchic system wherein everyone wants to be a chief leader,

30
00:03:31,137 --> 00:03:34,300
But more, why do people never become truly individuals?

31
00:03:35,021 --> 00:03:39,467
Or as modern psychology would have it, individuated or truly self-actuated.

32
00:03:41,050 --> 00:03:43,993
There are many psychological reasons, I'm sure, as to why this is.

33
00:03:44,455 --> 00:03:48,379
But here, I'd like to centre on what happens when we believe something.

34
00:03:50,823 --> 00:03:57,431
It seems that when we believe something, we give up the struggle to find out whether what we have come to believe is really true or not.

35
00:03:57,935 --> 00:04:04,100
By belief here is meant to accept without criticism or personal investigation any statement made by another.

36
00:04:05,181 --> 00:04:09,786
Once we've taken this belief position, we blindly accept whatever is said to be true.

37
00:04:10,747 --> 00:04:15,031
If you tell young children that Father Christmas is coming down the chimney, they believe it.

38
00:04:15,532 --> 00:04:15,812
I did.

39
00:04:16,271 --> 00:04:17,973
I wrote letters and sent them up the chimney.

40
00:04:19,095 --> 00:04:22,677
If I was still doing that now, people might think me a little eccentric, to say the least.

41
00:04:23,738 --> 00:04:26,641
But I've heard other children questioning it.

42
00:04:27,500 --> 00:04:29,904
And I wrote secret letters asking for this and that.

43
00:04:30,204 --> 00:04:33,230
Since they never came, I realized it was all just a joke.

44
00:04:33,853 --> 00:04:35,877
So I stopped believing there was a Father Christmas.

45
00:04:36,458 --> 00:04:39,324
But while I believed in Father Christmas, I felt great.

46
00:04:40,024 --> 00:04:43,913
I felt really secure that I'd get everything I wanted.

47
00:04:44,673 --> 00:04:45,475
I was really happy.

48
00:04:46,096 --> 00:04:48,141
But of course, I was living under a delusion.

49
00:04:48,728 --> 00:04:52,074
I personally believe this to be a very healthy thing to do to children.

50
00:04:52,654 --> 00:04:57,384
When they find out adults have tricked them, it should create a healthy scepticism.

51
00:04:57,803 --> 00:04:59,086
They lose their gullibility.

52
00:05:00,428 --> 00:05:04,976
There's no way you can fool a five-year-old whose discovered adults don't always tell the truth.

53
00:05:07,040 --> 00:05:10,887
This happiness in my delusion about Father Christmas' ignorance is bliss.

54
00:05:11,459 --> 00:05:13,062
has an unfortunate side effect.

55
00:05:13,583 --> 00:05:17,689
For while I believed, that very belief blocked my investigative faculties.

56
00:05:18,031 --> 00:05:19,233
It stifled my intellect.

57
00:05:19,653 --> 00:05:31,555
Worse, that belief destroyed the fine line between knowing a statement because I believe it to be true and knowing a statement because I discovered it to be true by my own experience.

58
00:05:31,995 --> 00:05:35,120
In other words, belief becomes knowledge.

59
00:05:35,100 --> 00:05:44,557
By force of my willingness to believe what my parents told me, by force of my own imagination, I believed Father Christmas to be as real as the presents I got from him.

60
00:05:47,221 --> 00:05:50,747
Although this seems rather trivial when talking about a child's belief in Father Christmas...

61
00:05:51,149 --> 00:05:56,776
When we look into history, we see so many examples of belief systems and what happens when someone undermines them.

62
00:05:57,416 --> 00:06:05,526
We need to remind ourselves that a belief system in Buddhism is seen as a self-definition, the self of opinions, views and judgments.

63
00:06:06,949 --> 00:06:07,949
I am what I believe.

64
00:06:08,670 --> 00:06:09,692
I am my opinions.

65
00:06:10,413 --> 00:06:13,817
If someone argues against what I believe and I win, I feel good.

66
00:06:14,478 --> 00:06:18,523
If in the argument I lose, I also lose my temper and call the other a fool.

67
00:06:19,279 --> 00:06:23,303
To actually change some of our cherished opinions can be very hard indeed.

68
00:06:24,766 --> 00:06:32,574
In the Middle Ages, for instance, people believed that man was the centre of God's creation, and therefore that the whole universe revolved about the earth, man's dwelling place.

69
00:06:33,514 --> 00:06:36,819
If you look up at the sky, that seems to be reinforced by observation.

70
00:06:37,259 --> 00:06:40,603
Indeed, the sun, moon and stars do appear to revolve around us.

71
00:06:41,704 --> 00:06:47,430
When Galileo discovered through his new telescope that in fact this was not so,

72
00:06:47,949 --> 00:06:52,297
He was told by the church authorities to be silent, or else he may find himself burnt as a heretic.

73
00:06:53,237 --> 00:07:02,894
In the Cultural Revolution in China, anyone even suspected of being a capitalist roder, or of believing that communism may not have it all right, meant imprisonment or execution.

74
00:07:03,995 --> 00:07:14,312
In our present-day secularist state, any idea of bringing some moral judgment to bear in laws concerning abortion, surrogate motherhood, and so on, are considered contrary to the idea of personal freedom.

75
00:07:15,119 --> 00:07:17,862
This idea of personal freedom can be taken to extremes.

76
00:07:19,004 --> 00:07:27,439
In America, study after study has shown that pornography is a chief factor in developing sexist attitudes and in influencing men towards sexual violence.

77
00:07:28,680 --> 00:07:35,271
A law enabling women victims of pornography to bring civil actions against pornographers was repealed in the federal courts.

78
00:07:35,639 --> 00:07:39,988
The pornographers claimed it was against their constitutional right of free speech.

79
00:07:40,589 --> 00:07:49,529
They won, even though the courts accepted that pornography was a violation of women's civil rights to equality and safety from violence.

80
00:07:50,387 --> 00:07:56,360
The right to free speech, it seems, takes precedence overall, even when it's harming individuals and society.

81
00:07:57,281 --> 00:08:01,550
Here in this country, racists consider it part of free speech to go around insulting people.

82
00:08:02,112 --> 00:08:06,641
It's now against the law, but not after a lot of damage had been done to community relations.

83
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:21,463
One of the outcomes of any belief system, religious, ideological, or whatever, is that the believers form a closed system, which not only has an answer to everything, but which has penalties for those believers who begin to doubt.

84
00:08:23,307 --> 00:08:26,211
If I didn't believe in Father Christmas, maybe I wouldn't get any presents.

85
00:08:27,555 --> 00:08:29,798
What happens to me if I don't believe in God anymore?

86
00:08:30,781 --> 00:08:33,085
If I don't believe Buddha was a fully enlightened being?

87
00:08:33,823 --> 00:08:38,751
Suddenly, I'm full of fear, and each system has horror tales of what happens to those who dare to leave.

88
00:08:39,251 --> 00:08:43,278
This is also true of Buddhism, when it had become an established religion.

89
00:08:43,980 --> 00:08:47,485
It's the way we human beings always like to build secure fortresses.

90
00:08:48,105 --> 00:08:49,467
But is it what the Buddha wanted?

91
00:08:51,672 --> 00:08:55,798
I think we can safely say that this was exactly the opposite of what the Buddha wanted.

92
00:08:56,234 --> 00:09:06,183
First of all, there are a lot of discourses written in the Socratic fashion, that is, the Buddha uses a question and answer format to get the listeners to discover for themselves the truth of the matter.

93
00:09:06,945 --> 00:09:18,775
Indeed, he uses this way of teaching in the very second discourse he gives on the characteristics of human existence, the transiency, unsatisfactoriness and insubstantiality of our lives.

94
00:09:20,177 --> 00:09:23,541
He asks, is the body permanent or not permanent?

95
00:09:23,892 --> 00:09:28,417
If it is impermanent and subject to change, can we say it belongs to a me?

96
00:09:29,077 --> 00:09:30,700
Or say it is what I am?

97
00:09:31,221 --> 00:09:34,144
Or say it constitutes a substantial soul or self?

98
00:09:34,725 --> 00:09:37,869
To all these questions, the listeners answer, no, venerable sir.

99
00:09:38,870 --> 00:09:44,155
And so he goes through all the rest of the aggregates, the sensations, perceptions, volitional conditionings and consciousness.

100
00:09:45,297 --> 00:09:53,427
One often gets from the scriptures whole passages where the Buddha is in conversation with one or another individual, usually beginning with a question and answer session.

101
00:09:54,048 --> 00:09:59,874
Only when he sees they've got the point does he then give a talk as such to clarify his own teachings.

102
00:10:00,855 --> 00:10:06,280
There is always the presumption that all that needs to be done is to dispel ignorance and wisdom will arise automatically.

103
00:10:07,201 --> 00:10:11,746
We are all capable of enlightenment, but we must all make the effort to achieve it.

104
00:10:12,869 --> 00:10:24,020
The Buddha's method is to excite a person's intellectual factors, get them thinking for themselves, and then make a clear statement of his own position, allowing the individual room to criticise and question.

105
00:10:25,874 --> 00:10:30,039
The second factor is his direct teaching on belief itself.

106
00:10:31,261 --> 00:10:37,190
There seems to have been an oversupply of religious teachers in his time with all sorts of teachings being expounded.

107
00:10:38,130 --> 00:10:39,513
A little bit like today, I imagine.

108
00:10:40,534 --> 00:10:43,999
The Buddha, while visiting the village of the Kalamas, was approached by them.

109
00:10:44,659 --> 00:10:53,011
They complained that one guru came and taught such and such and then another would come, call the other a fool and teach another set of doctrines.

110
00:10:53,701 --> 00:10:57,125
The point was that they were all very confused and didn't know what to believe.

111
00:10:57,946 --> 00:11:03,813
The Buddha then gives a talk which can rightly be called a declaration of an individual's right to freedom of thought.

112
00:11:05,895 --> 00:11:21,936
Do not believe anything simply because you have heard it, simply because it is tradition handed down for many generations, simply because it is spoken and rumoured by the many, simply because it is found written in your religious books.

113
00:11:22,557 --> 00:11:38,658
simply on the authority of your teachers and elders not only do we see in this discourse that the buddha had no desire for people to sell their souls to his teachings a blind belief but he exhorted them to think for themselves

114
00:11:39,719 --> 00:11:46,373
There is an incident in the scriptures which reinforces this picture of the Buddha as one who did not want people to be blind adherents.

115
00:11:47,134 --> 00:11:53,246
There was a certain Upali who when he had questioned the Buddha and heard him explain the doctrine was immediately converted.

116
00:11:54,428 --> 00:12:00,140
He was a major supporter of another important sect at the time and which still survives in India today, the Jains.

117
00:12:00,913 --> 00:12:09,725
The Buddha would not accept him as a follower immediately, but asked him to go back to the Jains and stay with them until he was absolutely sure of what he wanted to do.

118
00:12:10,966 --> 00:12:18,816
The Buddha knew that often people are caught up in their enthusiasm, only to feel embarrassed once the excitement has worn off.

119
00:12:18,836 --> 00:12:21,058
He really did want people to think about things.

120
00:12:22,880 --> 00:12:28,288
The third factor that points to the Buddha not wanting people to have blind belief in what he said

121
00:12:28,875 --> 00:12:35,081
is that he would not make any definite statements about matters that could not be verified, not be proven.

122
00:12:35,883 --> 00:12:38,004
He calls such questions undetermined.

123
00:12:38,985 --> 00:12:50,037
In a particular discourse named after the wealthy Brahmin he was talking to, Pottapada, he makes it clear the sort of philosophical, metaphysical questions he will not determine or give an answer to.

124
00:12:51,317 --> 00:12:54,721
Is the world eternal or not eternal, finite or infinite?

125
00:12:55,041 --> 00:12:58,764
Is the soul the same as the body, or is the soul one thing and the body another?

126
00:12:59,369 --> 00:13:01,873
Does an enlightened being live on after death or not?

127
00:13:02,533 --> 00:13:06,039
Or does he neither live nor not live again after death?

128
00:13:07,522 --> 00:13:14,393
You can see from these questions they are the sort of questions philosophers, both the professional armchair varieties, love to spend a lifetime talking about.

129
00:13:15,414 --> 00:13:19,782
To the exasperated Bhattapada, the Buddha explains why he expresses no opinion.

130
00:13:20,683 --> 00:13:25,191
Such questions, he says, bring no profit and are not concerned with the Dharma.

131
00:13:25,643 --> 00:13:29,828
They don't help to refine our moral behavior and develop non-attachment.

132
00:13:30,450 --> 00:13:33,833
Nor do they purify the mind and lead to the cessation of desire.

133
00:13:34,495 --> 00:13:39,982
Nor to equanimity, nor to supramundane knowledge, nor to the highest wisdom, nibbana.

134
00:13:41,325 --> 00:13:47,854
In other words, the Buddha would not be drawn into statements that were of no moral worth and did not lead to the end of suffering.

135
00:13:48,592 --> 00:14:00,047
In the context of the times these were the sorts of questions any self-respecting religious teacher was happy to give an answer to although there was a sect who, like the Buddha, would not enter into such discussions.

136
00:14:01,227 --> 00:14:07,495
The point is that the Buddha would not enter into useless arguments about things that could not be verified, not be proved.

137
00:14:08,557 --> 00:14:17,267
To have done so would have put his followers in a position of having to believe something they themselves could not verify and this would have led to an element of blind belief.

138
00:14:18,918 --> 00:14:25,527
So if the Buddha did not leave a set of unverifiable beliefs, he did not leave an empty philosophy or psychology either.

139
00:14:26,268 --> 00:14:32,758
And this is the fourth point that shows the Buddha did not want blind believers and indeed simply had no need of such support.

140
00:14:34,039 --> 00:14:40,369
The fact is that because he had discovered the truth by his own endeavour, he had also discovered the path to the truth.

141
00:14:41,230 --> 00:14:44,875
The Eightfold Noble Path is the great discovery of the Middle Way.

142
00:14:45,648 --> 00:14:48,831
He doesn't have to say to people, believe me, for I know this is true.

143
00:14:49,332 --> 00:14:55,260
He is free to say, this is the truth, now you can discover it for yourselves, whether it is true or not.

144
00:14:55,902 --> 00:15:02,892
Firstly, by the use of your own intellectual powers, and secondly, by direct experience, through practicing the Eightfold Noble Path.

145
00:15:04,033 --> 00:15:10,322
What is more, through the practice of Vipassana Insight Meditation, you will discover the Absolute Truth for yourself.

146
00:15:11,964 --> 00:15:13,966
In other words, the Buddhas...

147
00:15:14,639 --> 00:15:23,187
not simply saying that he's enlightened, but that everyone can become so, and he leaves us the actual method by which we can achieve it.

148
00:15:23,748 --> 00:15:26,471
He doesn't want meditators to remain disciples.

149
00:15:26,811 --> 00:15:28,793
He wants them to become masters.

150
00:15:30,534 --> 00:15:39,364
These four points then, his method of teaching allowing the listener to think for themselves, his declaration of an individual's right to freedom of thought,

151
00:15:40,340 --> 00:15:45,589
No doctrine that was not verifiable, able to be proved to be true by each individual.

152
00:15:46,770 --> 00:15:52,720
And lastly, the actual method and practice he left whereby individuals can prove all this to be true for themselves.

153
00:15:54,082 --> 00:15:58,529
All of this points to the Buddha not wanting to have people have blind belief.

154
00:15:59,731 --> 00:16:01,094
But he did want them to have faith.

155
00:16:02,716 --> 00:16:05,942
The difference between belief and faith is crucial in Buddhist understanding.

156
00:16:06,547 --> 00:16:11,293
By belief here is meant an acceptance of a statement about something that cannot be proved.

157
00:16:12,254 --> 00:16:14,616
Here there are two types of statements worth pondering over.

158
00:16:15,557 --> 00:16:20,563
If I discuss a Walkman with a friend, I would be trying to define what a perfect Walkman is.

159
00:16:20,924 --> 00:16:24,969
A cassette radio, stereo, light earphones and rechargeable battery and so on.

160
00:16:25,870 --> 00:16:28,333
We would hopefully eventually arrive at the perfect Walkman.

161
00:16:28,953 --> 00:16:30,976
But this perfection only exists in my mind.

162
00:16:31,057 --> 00:16:31,798
It's a concept.

163
00:16:32,379 --> 00:16:33,600
The perfect Walkman.

164
00:16:34,136 --> 00:16:36,539
And this concept has all the attributes named above.

165
00:16:37,621 --> 00:16:40,664
Now suppose I say to my friend, where have you put my Walkman?

166
00:16:41,486 --> 00:16:44,571
We are no longer worried about what a Walkman is anymore.

167
00:16:44,971 --> 00:16:46,692
We're worried about where the object is.

168
00:16:47,134 --> 00:16:49,777
The object, the Walkman in this case, really exists.

169
00:16:50,899 --> 00:17:03,434
Now if we keep these two types of statements in mind, the question of what is something as opposed to where is something, we can see we come across great difficulties with questions concerning the supramundane, the supernatural.

170
00:17:04,208 --> 00:17:10,494
If we say a God is the perfect good, for example, a group of people should be able to come to a good definition.

171
00:17:11,455 --> 00:17:17,002
But because they have come even to a perfect definition about a God, it doesn't mean, therefore, that he or she exists.

172
00:17:18,003 --> 00:17:24,412
Just because I can build up a picture of the perfect human being doesn't mean that person will actually ever really exist.

173
00:17:25,573 --> 00:17:30,739
When we come to the question of where is God, now that's where we have problems.

174
00:17:31,141 --> 00:17:36,829
because no one has yet found God anywhere, or at least anywhere where another person can also find that God.

175
00:17:37,790 --> 00:17:43,259
If God could be pointed to in the way that I point to a person, no difficulty would exist.

176
00:17:43,279 --> 00:17:46,265
These are the sorts of arguments the Buddha would not enter into.

177
00:17:46,945 --> 00:17:49,690
That's why he wouldn't say what happened to a Buddha after death.

178
00:17:50,371 --> 00:17:56,540
Such things are indescribable, unprovable, in the way that you can prove that the body rots after death.

179
00:17:58,326 --> 00:18:03,711
So here is the first error that can be made by the meditator if he believes in what the Buddha says.

180
00:18:04,413 --> 00:18:11,259
There is a possibility of turning a concept into a fact, of believing that a concept actually exists apart from the mind that has it.

181
00:18:12,161 --> 00:18:14,021
Nibbāna, for instance, is never described.

182
00:18:14,303 --> 00:18:15,263
It's a bold statement.

183
00:18:15,364 --> 00:18:19,528
The end of suffering exists, and it isn't annihilation nor a heaven.

184
00:18:20,749 --> 00:18:24,772
But what a person experiences when all suffering has gone is never described.

185
00:18:25,494 --> 00:18:31,060
If nibbana could be described, then it would still belong to this type of existence.

186
00:18:31,642 --> 00:18:38,409
All words and concepts can only describe what is possible in our experience as human beings, no matter how imaginative.

187
00:18:40,151 --> 00:18:47,179
That which is beyond sense experience, beyond the experience of this world, is by definition inexplicable, undescribable.

188
00:18:48,200 --> 00:18:51,564
So to have an idea of what nibbana is would actually be a hindrance.

189
00:18:52,484 --> 00:18:55,468
For I would be trying to experience my idea of nibbana

190
00:18:56,073 --> 00:19:02,683
If or when I do experience my idea of Nibbana, I will only have experienced my idea of it, what I think it is.

191
00:19:03,664 --> 00:19:13,039
To come to a point where I believe that my experience of an idea of Nibbana, say a brilliant or bright light, is in fact Nibbana, is to be deluded.

192
00:19:13,760 --> 00:19:17,827
Therefore, when it comes to such things, the Buddha was silent.

193
00:19:19,444 --> 00:19:26,314
So, if belief simply means saying something really exists which can't be proved, what is faith?

194
00:19:27,194 --> 00:19:28,836
Faith has little to do with thinking.

195
00:19:29,518 --> 00:19:31,180
Faith is a disposition of the heart.

196
00:19:31,760 --> 00:19:32,582
It is a trusting.

197
00:19:33,182 --> 00:19:35,305
It is to set one's heart to something.

198
00:19:35,826 --> 00:19:37,146
It arouses confidence in us.

199
00:19:37,567 --> 00:19:42,714
This confidence leads to an open-mindedness, to a willingness to investigate for ourselves.

200
00:19:43,675 --> 00:19:46,278
It arouses energy, courage and determination.

201
00:19:46,866 --> 00:19:51,951
When the Buddha teaches the fact of the end of suffering Nibbana, he does so by way of argument.

202
00:19:52,593 --> 00:19:54,473
These arguments we might find persuasive.

203
00:19:55,375 --> 00:20:00,240
Because we are attracted by the arguments, we ask, well, how do we know it's true?

204
00:20:01,540 --> 00:20:07,586
The Buddha then gives us a method, a technique, which will lead us to such a personal experience, the Noble Eightfold Path.

205
00:20:08,728 --> 00:20:11,810
Again, persuaded by this argument, we begin to tread that path.

206
00:20:12,332 --> 00:20:15,674
At first, because we're not sure, we do it carefully, hesitatingly.

207
00:20:16,364 --> 00:20:19,528
But as we tread the path, we find that what the Buddha said is true.

208
00:20:20,269 --> 00:20:30,442
As we discover for ourselves that little bits of what the Buddha said are actually true for us personally, so we listen more attentively to what he has to say, and our trust in his guidance grows.

209
00:20:31,544 --> 00:20:34,287
As our trust grows, so does our dedication to the path.

210
00:20:34,968 --> 00:20:40,194
This trust, this faith, known as saddha, becomes one of the spiritual faculties.

211
00:20:40,309 --> 00:20:44,195
Without this faith, the second faculty, energy, could not arise.

212
00:20:44,756 --> 00:20:48,020
If I don't have confidence in something, I'm hardly going to give it a go.

213
00:20:48,682 --> 00:20:53,087
If I don't have confidence to dive off the high plank, I'm hardly going to climb up to it.

214
00:20:54,289 --> 00:20:57,273
Without confidence, faith, no energy.

215
00:20:58,134 --> 00:20:59,778
No energy, no concentration.

216
00:21:00,638 --> 00:21:02,461
No concentration, no awareness.

217
00:21:03,262 --> 00:21:05,246
Without these, no meditation at all.

218
00:21:05,506 --> 00:21:08,410
And with no meditation, no wisdom can arise.

219
00:21:10,111 --> 00:21:18,361
The five spiritual faculties of faith, energy, concentration, awareness and wisdom all depend on this ability to set one's heart to something.

220
00:21:19,461 --> 00:21:24,188
Interestingly, once a person has experienced Nibbana, this faculty is now called a power.

221
00:21:25,048 --> 00:21:33,058
For one who has experienced Nibbana, their faith in the Buddha's path is unshakable, for now they know for themselves the third noble truth of the end of suffering.

222
00:21:35,461 --> 00:21:38,244
So what exactly did the Buddha want us to have faith in?

223
00:21:38,865 --> 00:21:52,102
During the last journey of the Buddha, while he was making his way to Kusinara, where he passed into Parinibbana, total Nibbana, Ananda, his faithful attendant for the last 20 years, begins to get frightened when he realizes his master is going to die.

224
00:21:53,403 --> 00:21:56,647
With great anxiety, he asks the Buddha what will happen once he's gone.

225
00:21:57,087 --> 00:21:59,811
What will happen to the order, to the teaching, to him, Ananda?

226
00:22:00,372 --> 00:22:01,534
Who will guide them?

227
00:22:01,554 --> 00:22:04,116
Who will guide him once he, the teacher, has gone?

228
00:22:05,057 --> 00:22:06,359
Here is the Buddha's reply.

229
00:22:07,760 --> 00:22:08,281
Ananda,

230
00:22:08,903 --> 00:22:10,565
Be an island unto yourself.

231
00:22:11,226 --> 00:22:12,888
Be a refuge unto yourself.

232
00:22:13,249 --> 00:22:15,192
Seek no external refuge.

233
00:22:16,432 --> 00:22:21,661
Live with the Dhamma, the truth, the law as your island, the Dhamma as your refuge.

234
00:22:22,342 --> 00:22:24,545
Take no other external refuge.

235
00:22:26,366 --> 00:22:27,469
What is the Buddha saying here?

236
00:22:28,230 --> 00:22:32,816
He's saying that in the ultimate analysis there is only the individual seeker and the truth.

237
00:22:33,497 --> 00:22:37,122
The truth, the law, the Dhamma that he taught has six qualities.

238
00:22:37,472 --> 00:22:38,994
It is to be self-realized.

239
00:22:39,275 --> 00:22:40,936
No one can realize the truth for us.

240
00:22:41,938 --> 00:22:45,482
When we experience the ultimate truth of Nibbāna, the fruits are immediate.

241
00:22:46,423 --> 00:22:48,747
We experience the results of that experience at once.

242
00:22:50,328 --> 00:22:52,270
The Dhamma invites us to investigate it.

243
00:22:53,352 --> 00:22:56,056
It will lead to Nibbāna, the liberation of all suffering.

244
00:22:56,776 --> 00:23:01,422
And finally, it has to be understood, to be comprehended by each person individually.

245
00:23:02,784 --> 00:23:04,746
This is where our confidence is to be put.

246
00:23:05,266 --> 00:23:08,348
But the Buddha also said, who sees the Dharma, sees me.

247
00:23:09,049 --> 00:23:14,596
In other words, there is no separation between the truth and the expression of that truth within the person of the Buddha.

248
00:23:15,637 --> 00:23:21,023
To put trust in the Dharma is therefore also to put trust in the teacher of that Dharma, the Buddha himself.

249
00:23:22,065 --> 00:23:27,891
But once he had gone into Parinibbana, the only tangible thing left for his followers is the actual teachings.

250
00:23:28,311 --> 00:23:32,876
That's why he asked Ananda to make it his island, his island of refuge.

251
00:23:34,122 --> 00:23:37,606
This Dharma, this truth, however, is not something external to a person.

252
00:23:38,167 --> 00:23:40,231
It isn't a treasure chest to be found on an island.

253
00:23:40,853 --> 00:23:44,178
It is a treasure to be found within a person's heart and being.

254
00:23:44,818 --> 00:23:51,048
Therefore, the Buddha asks Ananda to take refuge in himself, to trust himself, to have confidence in himself.

255
00:23:52,049 --> 00:23:53,893
All beings are capable of enlightenment.

256
00:23:54,773 --> 00:24:00,383
The Buddha is asking us to have faith in ourselves because in the last analysis we can only free ourselves.

257
00:24:01,762 --> 00:24:03,184
The Buddhas only point the way.

258
00:24:03,486 --> 00:24:05,729
They can't save us from suffering.

259
00:24:05,749 --> 00:24:07,752
We have to pull ourselves out of it.

260
00:24:08,834 --> 00:24:17,067
By cultivating this confidence in ourselves, we are also cultivating confidence in all those who've trod the path and succeeded, the noble ones, the Aryas, the saints.

261
00:24:18,169 --> 00:24:27,483
So it is that by taking refuge in ourselves, we are also putting trust, taking refuge in all those who have achieved the enlightenment, the Aryan Sangha, the community of noble ones.

262
00:24:28,325 --> 00:24:32,308
In this way, Buddhists take refuge in the Buddha, the Dhamma and the Sangha.

263
00:24:32,328 --> 00:24:34,571
In this way, they take refuge in themselves.

264
00:24:36,493 --> 00:24:43,662
This is all the Buddha wanted his followers to do, not to believe blindly what he said, not to accept the words of the Master without due investigation.

265
00:24:44,242 --> 00:24:48,487
He called himself the Tathagata, one who has completed the path, the journey.

266
00:24:49,028 --> 00:24:53,653
He wants all to follow that path, but with the spirit of investigation, of personal endeavour.

267
00:24:54,374 --> 00:24:57,116
He wants us to experiment and discover it for ourselves.

268
00:24:57,619 --> 00:25:05,333
if it stands to reason, if it is conducive to the benefit of all, then put confidence in it, trust it, and most of all, live up to it.

269
00:25:06,414 --> 00:25:10,401
The Buddha didn't ask the Kalamas to become his disciples to become Buddhists.

270
00:25:11,242 --> 00:25:14,848
If the Buddha's path works for us, then we should work at it.

271
00:25:17,854 --> 00:25:19,936
I hope you found this talk interesting and helpful.

272
00:25:20,759 --> 00:25:22,582
May all of you be happy and peaceful.

273
00:25:23,242 --> 00:25:26,428
May all of you attain the nirvanic peace within.

